\section{Results}
\subsection{Measles}
\begin{figure}
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\linewidth]{r0=12.png}
    \caption{SIR model curve for $R_0 = 12$}
    \label{$R_0 = 12$}
\end{figure}

Figure\ref{$R_0 = 12$} shows the implemented SIR model with $R_0 = 12$. This curve looks drastically different from that of the observed. In the first week the case value immediately reaches it's peak, then rapidly decreases around week 2. By week five the case count reaches zero and stays constant for the remaining weeks. It is evident based off this curve that that SIR model did not equality produce the observed data.

\begin{figure}
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\linewidth]{R_0=15.png}
    \caption{SIR model curve for $R_0 = 15$}
    \label{fig:$R_0 = 15$}
\end{figure}

Figure\ref{fig:$R_0 = 15$} shows the implemented SIR model with $R_0 = 15$. This plot's trend is virtually identical to the plot of $R_0 = 12$. The noticeable differences being that the peak case value was higher, with it being approximately 5,000 cases compared to the $R_0 = 12$ peak of approximately 4,700. The $R_0 = 15$ case values post week one decreased more rapidly with the case value almost at zero imminently after the first week.

\begin{figure}
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\linewidth]{R_0=18.png}
    \caption{SIR model curve for $R_0 = 18$}
    \label{fig:$R_0 = 18$}
\end{figure}

Figure\ref{fig:$R_0 = 18$} is the least accurate of the three plots. The peak case value is the greatest of them all, which again the peak starts immediately at week 1 and then by week two completely drops to zero. Though none of the three plots accurately represented the observed curve, what became clear is that the smaller the $R_0$ value the better the SIR model performed. With this in mind we then attempted values outside of the cited range to see if we could obtain a more accurate looking plot.

\begin{figure}
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\linewidth]{R=2.png}
    \caption{$R_0 = 2$}
    \label{fig:R_0 = 2}
\end{figure}

in Figure\ref{fig:R_0 = 2} we lowered the $R_0$ value significantly to $R_0= 2$, far out of the measles cited range. With such a low value this plot no longer represents an epidemic curve for measles, however, it does show a far more realistic shape. The curve has a rapid growth over the first weeks, reaches a clear peak, and then rapidly decreases to zero. This pattern is similar to that of the observed outbreak curve. This makes it clear that the SIR model better replicates an epidemic curve when it has a lower $R_0$ value. Measles in cited to have one of the highest $R_0$ values of all infectious diseases. This suggests that the SIR model is not a good fit for a disease such as measles with this extremely high value, but it may be more effective when other diseases are implemented. We then look at the results of COVID-19, a infectious diseases with a much lower $R_0 value$. 

\section{Limitations}

The SIR model is a very simple epidemic model. We stated that the model assuming homogeneous mixing, which is unrealistic. Entire populations do not have homogeneous mixing. This then forced us to use a smaller population size in our model, which could definitely effect the results. The $R_0$ appeared to have a strong influence over the model. If we revisit was this value is, it is the basic reproduction number, which is the number of individuals that one infected person can infect on average. So, when an infectious disease has a high $R_0$ value and the model assumes homogeneous mixing, the model infects almost everyone imminently. This makes sense, if one person can infect on average 18 people and everyone in the population has the same probability of coming into contact with that individual, it would not take long for the full population to be infected.


